  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(11) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "He hath turned aside.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The terror caused by the lion turns the traveller from his path, and there is no other; and then comes the attack by which he is torn in pieces.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He hath made me desolate.—Better, made me astonied, as in Ezra 9:3. The verb (which occurs forty times in Jeremiah’s prophecies and three times in Lam.), paints the stupefaction of terror.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "He hath made me desolate.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Better, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "made me astonied, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "as in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Ezra 9:3",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". The verb (which occurs forty times in Jeremiah’s prophecies and three times in Lam.), paints the stupefaction of terror.",
            "children": []
